Every new student who enrolls in Warren County Public Schools needs accounts in eight places: Active Directory, Google Workspace, the LMS (Canvas), PowerSchool, the library system, the food service platform, the device management system, and the district's SSO provider.

Before this system, each of those accounts was created manually — a checklist task for IT staff that happened once per enrollment event. With hundreds of enrollments each semester and a non-trivial transfer rate mid-year, the lag between SIS enrollment and full account readiness was measured in days.

## Architecture: event-driven provisioning

The system is built around an event bus (Azure Service Bus). The SIS publishes enrollment events — `student.enrolled`, `student.transferred`, `student.graduated`, `student.withdrawn` — as messages. Each downstream platform has a dedicated consumer service that handles only the messages relevant to it.

This architecture means:

- Adding a new downstream system requires only a new consumer — the SIS and other consumers are untouched
- A transient failure in one platform (e.g. the LMS API is down) does not block provisioning in others
- Each consumer can have its own retry policy appropriate to its upstream API's behaviour
- The full provisioning history is captured in the message log

```go
// Each provisioner implements a simple interface
type Provisioner interface {
    HandleEnrollment(ctx context.Context, event EnrollmentEvent) error
    HandleTransfer(ctx context.Context, event TransferEvent) error  
    HandleWithdrawal(ctx context.Context, event WithdrawalEvent) error
    SystemName() string
}
```

## Timing and sequencing

Some platforms have dependencies: the SSO provider needs Active Directory to exist before it can federate identity. The provisioning orchestrator maintains a dependency graph and ensures ordering, while still parallelising independent provisions.

The sequencing logic uses a simple topological sort at startup to produce an ordered provision plan. Any cycle in the dependency graph (which would indicate a configuration error) is detected and reported immediately rather than manifesting as a deadlock at runtime.

## The rollback problem

Partial provisioning is worse than no provisioning. If a student gets an AD account and a Google account but the LMS provisioning fails, they can log in but cannot access their courses — a confusing state that is harder to diagnose than "not provisioned yet."

The system handles this with a two-phase approach: each provisioner's `HandleEnrollment` first checks whether it can successfully provision (validating inputs, checking for conflicts) before actually doing so. If any provisioner's preflight check fails, none of the provisions proceed. Real-world failures during the actual provisioning step (network errors, rate limits) are retried with exponential backoff before triggering an alert.

## Outcome

Average time from SIS enrollment to all-platforms-ready: 11 minutes. The IT team's manual provisioning checklist was retired. Deprovisioning on withdrawal — previously the most error-prone part of the workflow — is now automated and leaves an audit trail.
